1. A post by an animal rights activism organisation depicting a tiger being forced to jump through rings of fire for peoples' entertainment. That it doesn't want to jump through the rings is presented as truth when we can't really know. It's fine to share but it anthropomorphises the tiger and implies things that don't seem to be verified, or even verifiable, although it is reasonable to assume that the tiger would have better welfare in the wild outside of human captivity.

2. A homeopathy page advocating for the efficacy of alternative medicine with reference to a study conducted by the Northern Irish government. We don't know whether the study is legitimate, whether it has been published by a peer-reviewed journal or whether it exists at all from the tweet alone. Not safe to share without further knowledge.

3. A photo of some sort of desert. No concerns.

Q86: A major problem that news has these days is that it quotes anonymous sources dredged up from social media. This reduces the credibility of any news I think, when they're referencing "something said on social media", which is often nonsense. Sadly people have a limited capacity to recognize this as such (nonsense) and so credible news outlets along with respected journalists have an important responsibility to cite only reliable, truthful, and independent/objectively verifiable sources of information. I'm skeptical of all news, especially what's found online.
